1
00:00:00,420 --> 00:00:02,280
We would never have cash around just to

2
00:00:02,280 --> 00:00:02,920
have cash.

3
00:00:03,019 --> 00:00:04,100
I mean, we would never think that we

4
00:00:04,100 --> 00:00:06,140
should have a cash position of X percent.

5
00:00:06,400 --> 00:00:08,780
And, frankly, I think these asset allocation things

6
00:00:08,780 --> 00:00:10,840
that tacticians in Wall Street put out, you

7
00:00:10,840 --> 00:00:12,800
know, about 60 percent stocks and 30 percent

8
00:00:12,800 --> 00:00:14,620
– we think that's total nonsense.

9
00:00:15,460 --> 00:00:17,480
So we want to have all our money

10
00:00:17,480 --> 00:00:20,640
working in decent businesses, but sometimes we can't

11
00:00:20,640 --> 00:00:22,660
find them or sometimes cash comes in unexpectedly

12
00:00:22,660 --> 00:00:26,720
or sometimes we sell something and we have

13
00:00:26,720 --> 00:00:28,420
more cash around than we would like.

14
00:00:28,420 --> 00:00:30,540
And more cash around than we would like

15
00:00:30,540 --> 00:00:32,000
means that we'd have 10 or 15 cents

16
00:00:32,000 --> 00:00:36,280
around because we want money employed, but we'll

17
00:00:36,280 --> 00:00:37,620
never employ it, just employ it.

18
00:00:37,740 --> 00:00:40,800
And you will find us quite unhappy over

19
00:00:40,800 --> 00:00:43,200
time if cash just keeps building up.

20
00:00:43,520 --> 00:00:45,000
And I think one way or another we'll

21
00:00:45,000 --> 00:00:46,000
find ways to use it.

22
00:00:46,360 --> 00:00:49,420
You may have trouble believing this, but Charlie

23
00:00:49,420 --> 00:00:50,980
and I never have an opinion about the

24
00:00:50,980 --> 00:00:53,460
market because it wouldn't be any good and

25
00:00:53,460 --> 00:00:55,700
it might interfere with the opinions we have

26
00:00:55,700 --> 00:00:56,280
that are good.

27
00:00:56,280 --> 00:00:59,400
If we're right about a business, if we

28
00:00:59,400 --> 00:01:02,020
think a business is attractive, it would be

29
00:01:02,020 --> 00:01:06,180
very foolish for us to not take action

30
00:01:06,180 --> 00:01:08,680
on that because we thought something about what

31
00:01:08,680 --> 00:01:11,160
the market was going to do or anything

32
00:01:11,160 --> 00:01:13,920
of that sort because we just don't know.

33
00:01:14,360 --> 00:01:17,140
And to give up something that you do

34
00:01:17,140 --> 00:01:19,900
know and that is profitable for something that

35
00:01:19,900 --> 00:01:22,360
you don't know and won't know because of

36
00:01:22,360 --> 00:01:25,380
that, it just doesn't make any sense to

37
00:01:25,380 --> 00:01:26,880
us and it doesn't really make any difference

38
00:01:26,880 --> 00:01:27,180
to us.

39
00:01:27,360 --> 00:01:28,300
There's nothing magic.

40
00:01:28,580 --> 00:01:30,020
We like to put a lot of money

41
00:01:30,020 --> 00:01:32,440
in things that we feel strongly about.

42
00:01:32,960 --> 00:01:35,140
And that gets back to the diversification question.

43
00:01:35,820 --> 00:01:39,760
We think diversification, as practiced generally, makes very

44
00:01:39,760 --> 00:01:41,340
little sense for anyone that knows what they're

45
00:01:41,340 --> 00:01:41,620
doing.

46
00:01:42,080 --> 00:01:44,040
Diversification is a protection against ignorance.

47
00:01:44,220 --> 00:01:45,840
I mean, if you want to make sure

48
00:01:45,840 --> 00:01:49,120
that nothing bad happens to you relative to

49
00:01:49,120 --> 00:01:50,160
the market, you own everything.

50
00:01:50,260 --> 00:01:51,200
There's nothing wrong with that.

51
00:01:51,200 --> 00:01:53,400
I mean, that is a perfectly sound approach

52
00:01:53,400 --> 00:01:56,020
for somebody who does not feel they know

53
00:01:56,020 --> 00:01:57,220
how to analyze businesses.

54
00:01:57,540 --> 00:01:59,960
If you know how to analyze businesses and

55
00:01:59,960 --> 00:02:03,320
value businesses, it's crazy to own 50 stocks

56
00:02:03,320 --> 00:02:05,700
or 40 stocks or 30 stocks probably because

57
00:02:05,700 --> 00:02:08,720
there aren't that many wonderful businesses that are

58
00:02:08,720 --> 00:02:11,300
understandable to a single human being in all

59
00:02:11,300 --> 00:02:11,700
likelihood.

60
00:02:11,960 --> 00:02:15,880
And to have some super wonderful business and

61
00:02:15,880 --> 00:02:18,440
then put money in number 30 or 35

62
00:02:18,440 --> 00:02:20,940
on your list of attractiveness and forego putting

63
00:02:20,940 --> 00:02:23,040
more money into number one just strikes Charlie

64
00:02:23,040 --> 00:02:24,660
and me as madness.

65
00:02:25,200 --> 00:02:27,820
It's conventional practice and if all you have

66
00:02:27,820 --> 00:02:31,100
to achieve is average, it's a confession in

67
00:02:31,100 --> 00:02:32,980
our view that you don't really understand the

68
00:02:32,980 --> 00:02:33,920
businesses that you own.

69
00:02:34,040 --> 00:02:36,520
On a personal portfolio basis, I own one

70
00:02:36,520 --> 00:02:38,580
stock, but it's a business I know.

71
00:02:39,000 --> 00:02:40,540
And it leaves me very comfortable.

72
00:02:41,940 --> 00:02:43,960
Do I need to own 28 stocks in

73
00:02:43,960 --> 00:02:45,560
order to have proper diversification?

74
00:02:46,080 --> 00:02:47,280
It would be nonsense.

75
00:02:47,280 --> 00:02:48,680
Three wonderful businesses.

76
00:02:49,320 --> 00:02:50,560
It's more than you need in this life

77
00:02:50,560 --> 00:02:51,360
to do very well.

78
00:02:51,460 --> 00:02:52,800
The average person isn't going to run into

79
00:02:52,800 --> 00:02:52,960
that.

80
00:02:53,020 --> 00:02:53,660
I mean, if you look at how the

81
00:02:53,660 --> 00:02:56,140
fortunes were built in this country, they weren't

82
00:02:56,140 --> 00:02:58,340
built out of a portfolio of 50 companies.

83
00:02:58,440 --> 00:03:00,860
They were built by someone who identified with

84
00:03:00,860 --> 00:03:02,460
a wonderful business.

85
00:03:02,600 --> 00:03:05,680
Much of what is taught in modern corporate

86
00:03:05,680 --> 00:03:08,100
finance courses is twaddle.

87
00:03:10,340 --> 00:03:12,220
Volatility does not measure risk.

88
00:03:12,220 --> 00:03:16,040
And the problem is that the people who

89
00:03:16,040 --> 00:03:17,640
have written and taught about risk do not

90
00:03:17,640 --> 00:03:19,180
know how to measure risk.

91
00:03:19,900 --> 00:03:22,080
And the nice thing about data, which is

92
00:03:22,080 --> 00:03:25,240
a measure of volatility, is that it's nice

93
00:03:25,240 --> 00:03:28,880
and mathematical and wrong in terms of measuring

94
00:03:28,880 --> 00:03:29,180
risk.

95
00:03:29,320 --> 00:03:32,260
It's a measure of volatility, but past volatility

96
00:03:32,260 --> 00:03:35,820
does not determine the risk of investing.

97
00:03:35,820 --> 00:03:38,320
I mean, actually take it with farmland here.

98
00:03:38,400 --> 00:03:41,880
In the early 1980s, farms that sold for

99
00:03:41,880 --> 00:03:45,280
$2,000 an acre went to $600 an

100
00:03:45,280 --> 00:03:45,520
acre.

101
00:03:46,080 --> 00:03:50,940
I bought one of them when the banking

102
00:03:50,940 --> 00:03:53,160
and farm crash took place.

103
00:03:53,880 --> 00:03:57,240
And the beta of farms shot way up.

104
00:03:58,980 --> 00:04:04,280
And according to standard economic theory, market theory,

105
00:04:04,440 --> 00:04:06,580
I was buying a much more risky asset

106
00:04:06,580 --> 00:04:09,860
at $600 an acre than the same farm

107
00:04:09,860 --> 00:04:11,140
was at $2,000 an acre.

108
00:04:11,760 --> 00:04:15,260
Now, people, because farmland doesn't trade often and

109
00:04:15,260 --> 00:04:17,720
prices don't get recorded, you know, they would

110
00:04:17,720 --> 00:04:20,500
regard that as nonsense, that my purchase at

111
00:04:20,500 --> 00:04:22,260
$600 an acre of the same farm that

112
00:04:22,260 --> 00:04:23,520
sold for $2,000 an acre a few

113
00:04:23,520 --> 00:04:24,620
years ago was riskier.

114
00:04:24,620 --> 00:04:27,960
But in SOX, because the prices jiggle around

115
00:04:27,960 --> 00:04:31,400
every minute, and because it lets the people

116
00:04:31,400 --> 00:04:35,840
who teach finance use the mathematics they've learned,

117
00:04:36,840 --> 00:04:40,680
they have, in effect, they would explain this

118
00:04:40,680 --> 00:04:42,920
away a little more technically, but they have,

119
00:04:43,020 --> 00:04:45,960
in effect, translated past volatility in terms of

120
00:04:45,960 --> 00:04:47,300
all kinds of measures of risk.

121
00:04:47,520 --> 00:04:48,800
And it's nonsense.

122
00:04:49,040 --> 00:04:52,860
Risk comes from the nature of certain kinds

123
00:04:52,860 --> 00:04:53,440
of businesses.

124
00:04:53,440 --> 00:04:55,320
It can be risky to be in some

125
00:04:55,320 --> 00:04:58,780
businesses just by the simple economics of the

126
00:04:58,780 --> 00:05:00,020
type of business you're in.

127
00:05:01,140 --> 00:05:03,180
And it comes from not knowing what you're

128
00:05:03,180 --> 00:05:03,520
doing.

129
00:05:04,900 --> 00:05:10,840
And, you know, if you understand the economics

130
00:05:10,840 --> 00:05:13,740
of the business in which you are engaged

131
00:05:13,740 --> 00:05:15,720
and you know the people with whom you're

132
00:05:15,720 --> 00:05:18,100
doing business and you know the price you

133
00:05:18,100 --> 00:05:21,700
pay is sensible, you don't run any real

134
00:05:21,700 --> 00:05:21,960
risk.

135
00:05:21,960 --> 00:05:24,060
And I don't think Charlie and I, certainly

136
00:05:24,060 --> 00:05:28,320
at Berkshire, I don't think we've ever had

137
00:05:28,320 --> 00:05:33,280
a permanent loss in marketable securities that was,

138
00:05:33,780 --> 00:05:35,500
what, 1 percent maybe?

139
00:05:35,800 --> 00:05:37,200
Half a percent of net worth?

140
00:05:37,440 --> 00:05:39,860
I made a terrible mistake in buying Dexter

141
00:05:39,860 --> 00:05:45,220
Shoe, which cost us significantly more than 1

142
00:05:45,220 --> 00:05:46,920
percent of net worth where I bought an

143
00:05:46,920 --> 00:05:48,040
entire business then.

144
00:05:48,280 --> 00:05:49,920
But I was wrong about the business.

145
00:05:50,640 --> 00:05:52,500
It had nothing to do with the volatility

146
00:05:52,500 --> 00:05:55,880
of shoe prices or leather or anything else.

147
00:05:56,020 --> 00:05:56,860
It just was wrong.

148
00:05:58,440 --> 00:06:00,840
But in terms of marketable securities, I cannot

149
00:06:00,840 --> 00:06:03,280
recall a case where we've lost.

150
00:06:03,420 --> 00:06:04,860
I mean, we've done a lot of things

151
00:06:04,860 --> 00:06:08,540
in securities that had a very high beta.

152
00:06:08,880 --> 00:06:10,260
We've done a lot of things in securities

153
00:06:10,260 --> 00:06:10,860
that had a low beta.

154
00:06:11,420 --> 00:06:16,920
It's just the whole development of volatility as

155
00:06:16,920 --> 00:06:18,860
a measure of risk, we've never found a

156
00:06:18,860 --> 00:06:20,020
way for it to be useful to us.

157
00:06:20,160 --> 00:06:24,100
Both corporate finance and investment management courses, as

158
00:06:24,100 --> 00:06:27,000
taught in the major universities, we would argue

159
00:06:27,000 --> 00:06:29,180
it's at least 50 percent twaddle.

160
00:06:29,620 --> 00:06:31,760
Yet these people have very high IQs.

161
00:06:32,560 --> 00:06:34,940
One of the reasons we've been able to

162
00:06:34,940 --> 00:06:38,700
do pretty well is that we early recognized

163
00:06:38,700 --> 00:06:43,700
that very smart people do very dumb things,

164
00:06:44,160 --> 00:06:46,040
and we tried to figure out why.

165
00:06:46,940 --> 00:06:48,680
And we also wanted to know who so

166
00:06:48,680 --> 00:06:49,560
we could avoid them.

167
00:06:49,940 --> 00:06:52,180
It's a temperamental quality, not an intellectual quality.

168
00:06:52,360 --> 00:06:53,940
You don't need tons of IQ in this

169
00:06:53,940 --> 00:06:54,220
business.

170
00:06:54,400 --> 00:06:55,380
I mean, you have to have enough IQ

171
00:06:55,380 --> 00:06:56,700
to get from here to downtown Omaha.

172
00:06:57,040 --> 00:06:59,740
But you do not have to be able

173
00:06:59,740 --> 00:07:01,840
to play three-dimensional chess or be in

174
00:07:01,840 --> 00:07:03,740
the top leagues in terms of bridge playing

175
00:07:03,740 --> 00:07:04,540
or something of the sort.

176
00:07:04,780 --> 00:07:08,380
You need a stable personality.

177
00:07:08,380 --> 00:07:11,920
You need a temperament that neither derives great

178
00:07:11,920 --> 00:07:14,060
pleasure from being with the crowd or against

179
00:07:14,060 --> 00:07:16,180
the crowd because this is not a business

180
00:07:16,180 --> 00:07:17,020
where you take polls.

181
00:07:17,140 --> 00:07:18,180
It's a business where you think.

182
00:07:19,120 --> 00:07:20,640
And Ben Graham would say that you're not

183
00:07:20,640 --> 00:07:23,280
right or wrong because 1,000 people agree

184
00:07:23,280 --> 00:07:25,240
with you, and you're not right or wrong

185
00:07:25,240 --> 00:07:26,740
because 1,000 people disagree with you.

186
00:07:26,760 --> 00:07:28,420
You're right because your facts and your reasoning

187
00:07:28,420 --> 00:07:28,880
are right.

188
00:07:29,180 --> 00:07:30,900
By far the best investment you can make

189
00:07:30,900 --> 00:07:31,600
is in yourself.

190
00:07:32,700 --> 00:07:34,400
For example, communication skills.

191
00:07:34,520 --> 00:07:36,680
I tell those students that come that they're

192
00:07:36,680 --> 00:07:40,560
going to graduate schools and business, and they're

193
00:07:40,560 --> 00:07:42,540
learning all these complicated formulas and all that.

194
00:07:42,540 --> 00:07:45,460
If they just learn to communicate better, both

195
00:07:45,460 --> 00:07:47,800
in writing and in person, they increase their

196
00:07:47,800 --> 00:07:48,940
value at least 50%.

197
00:07:48,940 --> 00:07:50,940
If you can't communicate, somebody says, you know,

198
00:07:50,960 --> 00:07:52,160
it's like winking at a girl in the

199
00:07:52,160 --> 00:07:52,460
dark.

200
00:07:52,600 --> 00:07:53,820
Nothing happens, you know, basically.

201
00:07:54,080 --> 00:07:55,700
And you have to be able to get

202
00:07:55,700 --> 00:07:57,840
forth your ideas.

203
00:07:58,320 --> 00:08:00,960
And that's relatively easy.

204
00:08:01,060 --> 00:08:03,620
I did it myself with the Dale Carnegie

205
00:08:03,620 --> 00:08:03,920
course.

206
00:08:04,320 --> 00:08:06,240
Some people wish I'd taken a shorter course

207
00:08:06,240 --> 00:08:08,260
now in terms of my talking later on.

208
00:08:08,620 --> 00:08:10,960
But it's just hugely important.

209
00:08:10,960 --> 00:08:13,320
And if you invest in yourself, nobody can

210
00:08:13,320 --> 00:08:14,220
take it away from you.

211
00:08:14,300 --> 00:08:15,440
If I gave you a car, and it'd

212
00:08:15,440 --> 00:08:16,940
be the only car you'd get the rest

213
00:08:16,940 --> 00:08:18,400
of your life, you'd take care of it

214
00:08:18,400 --> 00:08:19,200
like you can't believe it.

215
00:08:19,240 --> 00:08:20,600
Any scratch, you'd fix that moment.

216
00:08:20,740 --> 00:08:21,720
You'd read the owner's manual.

217
00:08:21,820 --> 00:08:23,100
You'd keep a garage and do all these

218
00:08:23,100 --> 00:08:23,360
things.

219
00:08:23,420 --> 00:08:26,180
And you get exactly one mind and one

220
00:08:26,180 --> 00:08:27,060
body in this world.

221
00:08:28,020 --> 00:08:29,880
And you can't start taking care of it

222
00:08:29,880 --> 00:08:30,460
when you're 50.

223
00:08:30,560 --> 00:08:32,140
By that time, you'll have rusted out if

224
00:08:32,140 --> 00:08:32,860
you haven't done anything.

225
00:08:33,080 --> 00:08:36,600
So you should really make sure that you

226
00:08:36,600 --> 00:08:39,240
just remember that you've just got one mind

227
00:08:39,240 --> 00:08:40,700
and body to get through life with and

228
00:08:40,700 --> 00:08:41,720
to do the most with it.

229
00:08:41,940 --> 00:08:44,640
We think the best way to minimize risk

230
00:08:44,640 --> 00:08:45,280
is to think.

231
00:08:46,480 --> 00:08:48,740
And the idea that you have, you know,

232
00:08:48,800 --> 00:08:50,880
you'll say, I've got 60% in stocks

233
00:08:50,880 --> 00:08:53,380
and 40% in bonds and then have

234
00:08:53,380 --> 00:08:54,920
a big announcement, now we're moving it to

235
00:08:54,920 --> 00:09:00,640
65-35 as some strategist or whatever they

236
00:09:00,640 --> 00:09:01,480
call them in Wall Street.

237
00:09:01,900 --> 00:09:03,840
I mean, that has to be pure nonsense.

238
00:09:03,840 --> 00:09:09,300
I mean, 60-40 or 65, it just

239
00:09:09,300 --> 00:09:10,200
doesn't make any sense.

240
00:09:10,560 --> 00:09:13,340
What you ought to do is have your

241
00:09:13,340 --> 00:09:16,200
default position is always short-term instruments.

242
00:09:16,340 --> 00:09:17,880
And whenever you see anything intelligent to do,

243
00:09:17,960 --> 00:09:18,720
you should do it.

244
00:09:18,960 --> 00:09:21,940
And you shouldn't be trying to match up

245
00:09:21,940 --> 00:09:23,460
with some goal like that.

246
00:09:23,520 --> 00:09:25,220
I found it entertaining.

247
00:09:25,340 --> 00:09:26,940
I was just reading yesterday an article, I

248
00:09:26,940 --> 00:09:29,420
think it was, about the two fellows at

249
00:09:29,420 --> 00:09:32,020
Google and all of the problems they're going

250
00:09:32,020 --> 00:09:33,160
to have because they're each going to get

251
00:09:33,160 --> 00:09:34,120
a few billion dollars.

252
00:09:35,080 --> 00:09:37,900
I mean, I wanted to send a sympathy

253
00:09:37,900 --> 00:09:38,200
card.

254
00:09:38,320 --> 00:09:40,320
I almost went down a Hallmark store because

255
00:09:40,320 --> 00:09:42,740
this article went on, they've got this terrible

256
00:09:42,740 --> 00:09:44,340
problem and that terrible problem and they're going

257
00:09:44,340 --> 00:09:45,420
to need lawyers and they're going to need

258
00:09:45,420 --> 00:09:45,960
financial aid.

259
00:09:46,040 --> 00:09:46,860
They don't need anybody.

260
00:09:47,240 --> 00:09:48,820
Those guys are smarter than the people that

261
00:09:48,820 --> 00:09:49,440
are coming to them.

262
00:09:50,100 --> 00:09:51,760
And they do not have a big problem.

263
00:09:52,180 --> 00:09:53,960
And they're very capable of thinking it through

264
00:09:53,960 --> 00:09:54,440
themselves.

265
00:09:55,020 --> 00:09:56,800
The people that have the problem are the

266
00:09:56,800 --> 00:09:58,600
people who want to sell their services to

267
00:09:58,600 --> 00:10:00,740
them and are going to have to convince

268
00:10:00,740 --> 00:10:01,740
them that they have a problem.

269
00:10:03,960 --> 00:10:07,140
But so much of what you see when

270
00:10:07,140 --> 00:10:10,120
you talk about asset allocations, it's just merchandising.

271
00:10:10,340 --> 00:10:11,920
It's a way to make you think that

272
00:10:11,920 --> 00:10:13,840
if you don't know how to determine whether

273
00:10:13,840 --> 00:10:16,020
